2. Create a new categorical variable named âobesity_levelâ using the BMI measurement (underweight BMI<14; normal BMI 14-22; overweight BMI 22-24; obese BMI>24)

categories <- c("Underweight", "Normal", "Overweight", "Obese")
chs_comb <- chs_comb[!is.na(chs_comb$bmi), ]
chs_comb$obesity_level <- cut(chs_comb$bmi,
                                        breaks = c(-Inf, 14, 22, 24, Inf),
                                        labels = categories)
summary_obesity <- chs_comb %>%
  group_by(obesity_level) %>%
  summarize(min_BMI = min(bmi),
            max_BMI = max(bmi),
            total_observations = n())

3. Create another categorical variable named âsmoke_gas_exposureâ that summarizes âSecond Hand Smokeâ and âGas Stove.â The variable should have four categories in total.

chs_comb <- chs_comb %>%
  mutate(smoke_gas_exposure = case_when(
    smoke == 1 & gasstove == 1 ~ "Both",
    smoke == 1 ~ "Second Hand Smoke",
    gasstove == 1 ~ "Gas Stove",
    TRUE ~ "None"
  ))

1. What is the association between BMI and FEV (forced expiratory volume)?

fev_bmi_summary <- chs_comb %>%
  group_by(obesity_level) %>%
  summarize(mean_fev = mean(fev, na.rm = TRUE))
fev_bmi_summary
# A tibble: 4 Ã 2
  obesity_level mean_fev
  <fct>            <dbl>
1 Underweight      1687.
2 Normal           1998.
3 Overweight       2224.
4 Obese            2269.
chs_comb <- chs_comb[!is.na(chs_comb$fev) & is.finite(chs_comb$fev), ]
ggplot(chs_comb, aes(x = bmi, y = fev)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  labs(title = "Scatterplot of BMI vs. FEV",
       x = "BMI",
       y = "FEV")
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

It seems that for the towns, BMI and FEV have an overall positive relationship with each other when looking at the regression model. When looking at the obesity levels, the mean appears to be increasing throughout the different levels from âUnderweightâ to âObese.â
